       <subsection>
            <title>Function Vocabulary</title>

            <definition>
                <title>domain</title>

                <statement>
                    <p>
                        The <alert>domain</alert> of a function <m>f</m> is the <em>largest</em> set of <em>real numbers</em> for which the value <em> <m>f(x)</m> </em> is a <em>real number</em>.
                        Things to look out for
                        <ul>
                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    Division by <em>zero</em>
                                </p>
                            </li>

                            <li>
                                <p>
                                    <em>Even</em> roots of <em>negative</em> numbers
                                </p>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                        NOTE: For word problems/verbal descriptions, the domain depends on the real-world <em>context</em> of the model.
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </definition>

            <p>
            </p>

            <example>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        <em>Finding the domain of a function from an equation</em>
                    </p>

                    <p>
                        <m>f(x)=3x+2</m>  <m>g(x)=\dfrac{3x+2}{x+1}</m>  <m>h(x)=\sqrt{x-3}</m>
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </example>

            <definition>
                <title>zero</title>

                <statement>
                    <p>
                        If <m>f</m> is a function and <m>r</m> is a real number for which <em> <m>f(r)=0</m> </em>, then <m>r</m> is a <alert>zero</alert> of <m>f</m>.
                        In other words, <m>r</m> is an <em>x-intercept</em> of the <em>graph</em> of <m>f</m>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </definition>

            <p>
            </p>

            <definition>
                <title>maximum</title>

                <statement>
                    <p>
                        The <alert>maximum</alert> of a function <m>f</m> is the <em>largest</em> value in the <em>range</em> of <m>f</m>.
                        On the graph of <m>f</m>, the maximum is the <em>y-coordinate</em> of a point at the <em>top</em> of a <em>peak</em>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </definition>

            <p>
            </p>

            <definition>
                <title>minimum</title>

                <statement>
                    <p>
                        The <alert>minimum</alert> of a function <m>f</m> is the <em>smallest</em> value in the <em>range</em> of <m>f</m>.
                        On the graph of <m>f</m>, the minimum is the <em>y-coordinate</em> of a point at the <em>bottom</em> of a <em>valley</em>.
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </definition>

            <p>
            </p>

            <definition>
                <title>even</title>

                <statement>
                    <p>
                        A function <m>f</m> is <alert>even</alert> if and only if it is symmetric with respect to the <em> <m>y</m>-axis</em>.
                        <em> <m>f(x)=f(-x)</m> </em> for every <m>x</m>-value in the domain of <m>f</m>
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </definition>

            <p>
            </p>

            <definition>
                <title>odd</title>

                <statement>
                    <p>
                        A function <m>f</m> is <alert>odd</alert> if and only if it is symmetric with respect to the <em>origin</em>.
                        <em> <m>f(-x)=-f(x)</m> </em> for every <m>x</m>-value in the domain of <m>f</m>
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </definition>

            <example>
                <statement>
                    <p>
                        <em>(Determining Symmetry from an Equation)</em>  <m>f(x)=x^{4}+3x^{2}-x</m>
                    </p>
                </statement>
            </example>

            <p>
            </p>
        </subsection>


