    <definition>
        <title>Inverse Function</title>

        <statement>
            <p>
                Let <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> be two functions such that
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>(f\circ g)(x)=f(g(x))=x</m> for every <m>x</m> in the domain of <m>g</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
                and
                <ul>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>(g\circ f)(x)=g(f(x))=x</m> for every <m>x</m> in the domain of <m>f</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ul>
                Then the function <m>g</m> is called the <alert>inverse function of <m>\mathbf{f}</m> </alert> and is denoted by <m>f^{-1}</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>

    <subsubsection>
        <title>Finding the Inverse of a Function</title>

        Given an equation:
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Change <m>f(x)</m> to <m>y</m> if needed.
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    Swap <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    Solve for <m>y</m>.
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    Change <m>y</m> to <m>f^{-1}(x)</m> if needed.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
        Given a graph:
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Swap individual coordinates &#x26;connect the dots: <m>(a,b)</m> on the original becomes <m>(b,a)</m> on the inverse.
                </p>
            </li>

            <li>
                <p>
                    Alternatively, reflect the entire graph over the line <m>y=x</m>.
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>

        <example>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <em>(Finding the inverse of a function from an equation.)</em> <m>f(x)=\dfrac{x+1}{x-2}</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </example>

        <p>
        </p>
    </subsubsection>
</subsection>


<subsection>
    <title>Inequalities Involving Functions</title>

    <p>
        General strategy: Treat inequalities like equations, then test points to determine which interval(s) to include in your solution.
    </p>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <m>|x-6|-3\leq-2</m>
            </p>
        </statement>
